I had to call you.

278
00:15:08,558 --> 00:15:12,118
Please, I need some help.

279
00:15:12,119 --> 00:15:13,279
Jimmy?

280
00:15:13,519 --> 00:15:15,638
I found a body, on the mountain.

281
00:15:15,639 --> 00:15:16,878
I found a body!

282
00:15:16,879 --> 00:15:17,678
What are you saying?

283
00:15:17,679 --> 00:15:18,398
What are you telling me?

284
00:15:18,399 --> 00:15:20,118
They never found a body.

285
00:15:20,119 --> 00:15:23,399
Don't you tell me that,
you little bastard!

286
00:15:23,400 --> 00:15:25,599
I'm an old woman,
and I wanna be left alone.

287
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:27,599
No, it's the IRA.

288
00:15:27,600 --> 00:15:29,319
They buried a man on the mountain.

289
00:15:29,320 --> 00:15:31,119
I found him.

290
00:15:31,120 --> 00:15:32,879
I have to get out of Belfast.

291
00:15:32,880 --> 00:15:34,999
Mr Quinlan said I should ask you.

292
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:36,439
What do you want me to do?

293
00:15:36,440 --> 00:15:38,000
Can I come and stay?

294
00:15:38,001 --> 00:15:40,680
What, come here?

295
00:15:40,681 --> 00:15:42,560
Please, just for a wee while.

296
00:15:42,561 --> 00:15:43,441
Please.

297
00:15:43,681 --> 00:15:45,960
But I don't even know you.

298
00:15:45,961 --> 00:15:48,200
Mr Quinlan wants me
to bring you the ring.

299
00:15:48,201 --> 00:15:50,961
I could give it to you... Please.

300
00:15:50,962 --> 00:15:55,802
Just for a couple of weeks,
till it blows over.

301
00:15:57,962 --> 00:16:03,843
Well all right, you can come.

302
00:16:04,803 --> 00:16:05,763
Hey, Jack.

303
00:16:06,003 --> 00:16:06,923
Chuck.

304
00:16:07,163 --> 00:16:08,083
Good trip?

305
00:16:08,283 --> 00:16:09,363
The worst.

306
00:16:10,083 --> 00:16:11,282
This one is Teddy's.

307
00:16:11,283 --> 00:16:12,363
Yeah.

308
00:16:12,723 --> 00:16:15,282
Looks like you got yourself
a story there

309
00:16:15,283 --> 00:16:16,363
Yeah.

310
00:16:18,164 --> 00:16:19,643
She been crying?

311
00:16:19,644 --> 00:16:20,164
No.

312
00:16:20,404 --> 00:16:21,244
I have.

313
00:16:21,484 --> 00:16:22,923
What happened to you?

314
00:16:22,924 --> 00:16:25,323
Oh, I got shot up over Bremen.

315
00:16:25,324 --> 00:16:28,563
Plexiglas in my eye
I might lose it.

316
00:16:28,564 --> 00:16:30,283
I can't fly, can't even shoot.

317
00:16:30,284 --> 00:16:31,724
I'm out of the war.

318
00:16:31,725 --> 00:16:33,484
Ethel Ann is looking after me now.

319
00:16:33,485 --> 00:16:38,245
That's good seeing how he
wanted you to take care of her.

320
00:16:38,765 --> 00:16:41,084
He should have asked you, Jack.

321
00:16:41,085 --> 00:16:43,885
She doesn't love me,
but I know she could love you.

322
00:16:43,886 --> 00:16:44,965
I wish he'd asked you, Jack.

323
00:16:44,966 --> 00:16:47,085
Well, he didn't.

324
00:16:47,086 --> 00:16:50,365
And we promised.

325
00:16:50,366 --> 00:16:52,845
You're the man, Chuck.

326
00:16:52,846 --> 00:16:56,286
Let's do this.

327
00:16:59,447 --> 00:17:00,367
Hi, Jack.

328
00:17:00,567 --> 00:17:01,686
You better come inside.

329
00:17:01,687 --> 00:17:03,406
What the hell is going on here?

330
00:17:03,407 --> 00:17:06,166
She doesn't tell me a damn thing,
just someone is coming to visit.

331
00:17:06,167 --> 00:17:06,767
Who?

332
00:17:07,007 --> 00:17:07,686
Where from?

333
00:17:07,687 --> 00:17:08,087
Ireland.

334
00:17:08,327 --> 00:17:08,727
Belfast.

335
00:17:08,967 --> 00:17:10,087
Belfast?

336
00:17:11,008 --> 00:17:12,367
I don't wanna leave her alone,
Jack,

337
00:17:12,368 --> 00:17:13,567
but I can't
take much more of this.

338
00:17:13,568 --> 00:17:14,008
All right.

339
00:17:14,288 --> 00:17:18,288
Go on, get out of here,
both of you.

340
00:17:20,368 --> 00:17:22,407
You look like hell.

341
00:17:22,408 --> 00:17:24,488
You wanted me to grieve

342
00:17:24,489 --> 00:17:26,128
Would you go to
the airport for me, please?

343
00:17:26,129 --> 00:17:27,008
I'll send Peter.

344
00:17:27,009 --> 00:17:28,488
No, I want you to go yourself.

345
00:17:28,489 --> 00:17:29,928
I don't even know who this guy is.

346
00:17:29,929 --> 00:17:30,608
Neither do I.

347
00:17:30,609 --> 00:17:32,888
Marie says he's from Belfast.

348
00:17:32,889 --> 00:17:34,448
Well,
that is none of her business.

349
00:17:34,449 --> 00:17:35,129
Look

350
00:17:35,409 --> 00:17:37,048
Ethel you have got to talk to her.

351
00:17:37,049 --> 00:17:39,129
Will you take your hands off me?

352
00:17:39,130 --> 00:17:41,049
And who the hell
do you know in Belfast?

353
00:17:41,050 --> 00:17:41,729
Who is this guy?

354
00:17:41,730 --> 00:17:43,289
His name is Jimmy Reilly,

355
00:17:43,290 --> 00:17:46,929
he's arriving at 12.10 tonight
on American 301.

356
00:17:46,930 --> 00:17:48,729
Would you meet him at the airport?

357
00:17:48,730 --> 00:17:52,010
You listen to me!

358
00:17:52,011 --> 00:17:55,690
If you don't talk to Marie now,
you're gonna lose her.

359
00:17:55,691 --> 00:17:57,850
She's gonna go.

360
00:17:57,851 --> 00:18:00,850
You just tell her what happened,
she'll understand.

361
00:18:00,851 --> 00:18:01,970
Listen to me.

362
00:18:01,971 --> 00:18:05,291
All the love she ever got
was from her daddy.

363
00:18:05,292 --> 00:18:07,771
All the kisses and hugs and
bedtime stories

364
00:18:07,772 --> 00:18:12,411
and cuddles never from me

365
00:18:12,412 --> 00:18:15,491
You think now
she will understand why?

366
00:18:15,492 --> 00:18:17,692
I think you should
give her the chance.

367
00:18:17,693 --> 00:18:20,132
Well that's what I intend to do.

368
00:18:20,133 --> 00:18:23,773
Now, please go.

369
00:18:34,494 --> 00:18:37,213
No, don't do that, please.

370
00:18:37,214 --> 00:18:39,413
Just... come on in.

371
00:18:39,414 --> 00:18:40,494
I'm sorry.

372
00:18:41,334 --> 00:18:43,293
I'm real glad you're safe.

373
00:18:43,294 --> 00:18:45,534
Look at that foot.

374
00:18:45,535 --> 00:18:47,934
Must be hard for you,
not racing around.

375
00:18:47,935 --> 00:18:48,855
Yeah.

376
00:18:52,015 --> 00:18:55,495
- Let me take these.
- Thanks.

377
00:18:57,215 --> 00:19:00,175
Did they find a body?

378
00:19:00,176 --> 00:19:01,296
No.

379
00:19:02,776 --> 00:19:04,535
So there's no proof?

380
00:19:04,536 --> 00:19:06,735
Ethel Ann, he's gone.

381
00:19:06,736 --> 00:19:09,495
We could arrange
a memorial service.

382
00:19:09,496 --> 00:19:10,536
Why?

383
00:19:12,097 --> 00:19:14,696
We're the only ones
who will remember him.

384
00:19:14,697 --> 00:19:17,976
There's no family now.

385
00:19:17,977 --> 00:19:21,457
No children.

386
00:19:26,578 --> 00:19:29,217
Was that his case I saw you
put in the hall?

387
00:19:29,218 --> 00:19:32,337
I brought his things
back for you, yeah.

388
00:19:32,338 --> 00:19:33,817
Let's bring it in.

389
00:19:33,818 --> 00:19:35,937
Open it up.

390
00:19:35,938 --> 00:19:37,377
There's plenty of time for that.

391
00:19:37,378 --> 00:19:38,299
No.

392
00:19:38,499 --> 00:19:40,338
No, let's do it now

393
00:19:40,339 --> 00:19:42,179
Please.

394
00:19:43,299 --> 00:19:44,219
Hiya.

395
00:19:44,459 --> 00:19:46,338
You must be Jimmy.

396
00:19:46,339 --> 00:19:47,458
How do you do?

397
00:19:47,459 --> 00:19:47,939
I'm great.

398
00:19:48,139 --> 00:19:49,178
I'm just great.

399
00:19:49,179 --> 00:19:49,898
Come in, please.

400
00:19:49,899 --> 00:19:50,818
Oh, thank you.

401
00:19:50,819 --> 00:19:53,980
Through there.

402
00:19:54,140 --> 00:19:56,379
Why did you do this?

403
00:19:56,380 --> 00:19:58,179
This is Jack's son, Peter.

404
00:19:58,180 --> 00:19:58,979
Jimmy Reilly.

405
00:19:58,980 --> 00:19:59,420
Hello.

406
00:19:59,620 --> 00:20:00,259
How do you do?

407
00:20:00,260 --> 00:20:00,899
Nice to meet you.

408
00:20:00,900 --> 00:20:02,419
Let me take that.

409
00:20:02,420 --> 00:20:04,339
And this is my daughter, Marie.

410
00:20:04,340 --> 00:20:05,340
Jimmy Reilly.

411
00:20:05,341 --> 00:20:07,900
Hello... How do you doody?!

412
00:20:07,901 --> 00:20:09,620
Did we speak on the phone?

413
00:20:09,621 --> 00:20:11,140
Sit down, Jimmy.

414
00:20:11,141 --> 00:20:12,300
How was the flight?

415
00:20:12,301 --> 00:20:14,900
Oh, it was fantastic.

416
00:20:14,901 --> 00:20:16,740
747 all the way.

417
00:20:16,741 --> 00:20:17,540
Well, not all the way.

418
00:20:17,541 --> 00:20:20,261
We had to fly to London first
then right across to New York.

419
00:20:20,262 --> 00:20:21,381
And they gave us meals and all.

420
00:20:21,382 --> 00:20:22,502
No charge.

421
00:20:22,742 --> 00:20:24,581
And they had little
things of salt and pepper,

422
00:20:24,582 --> 00:20:26,621
sachets, I've got some here.

423
00:20:26,622 --> 00:20:28,701
And they had little bottles of Irish.

424
00:20:28,702 --> 00:20:29,302
Free.

425
00:20:29,542 --> 00:20:30,741
And there was a film.

426
00:20:30,742 --> 00:20:34,302
And then we had to fly
from London to New York,

427
00:20:34,303 --> 00:20:37,582
then from New York to Detroit,
and from Detroit to Branagan.

428
00:20:37,583 --> 00:20:39,622
And it was really fantastic.

429
00:20:39,623 --> 00:20:42,222
Jack, do you remember
when we used to take two,

430
00:20:42,223 --> 00:20:45,143
three, maybe four days
to do the same thing?

431
00:20:45,144 --> 00:20:51,463
We'd have to go from Belfast
to Iceland to Newfoundland.

432
00:20:51,464 --> 00:20:52,744
Yes.

433
00:20:53,184 --> 00:20:55,423
Dad... you all right?

434
00:20:55,424 --> 00:20:58,704
Yeah, why don't you take
these cases upstairs.

435
00:20:58,705 --> 00:21:03,265
Oh, thank you,
but this one is for you.

436
00:21:03,625 --> 00:21:05,384
Mind if I put this on your table?

437
00:21:05,385 --> 00:21:06,304
No, go ahead.

438
00:21:06,305 --> 00:21:09,704
Just let me get the flowers there.

439
00:21:09,705 --> 00:21:11,104
They made me open it up.

440
00:21:11,105 --> 00:21:12,105
This whole thing is for me?

441
00:21:12,106 --> 00:21:12,546
Yes.

442
00:21:12,746 --> 00:21:16,266
They couldn't believe
what I had inside.

443
00:21:16,546 --> 00:21:18,145
Look at this.

444
00:21:18,146 --> 00:21:19,425
Part of the aileron.

445
00:21:19,426 --> 00:21:21,985
Starboard wing.

446
00:21:21,986 --> 00:21:25,506
And these are switches from
the radio operator's position.

447
00:21:25,507 --> 00:21:30,306
And this is a piece of
Plexiglas curved,

448
00:21:30,307 --> 00:21:32,346
from a gun turret.

449
00:21:32,347 --> 00:21:39,267
And this... a pressure gauge.

450
00:21:39,268 --> 00:21:40,628
Oxygen.

451
00:21:40,868 --> 00:21:43,307
They had to breathe oxygen,
you know, they went that high.

452
00:21:43,308 --> 00:21:44,907
Oh Jesus Christ.

453
00:21:44,908 --> 00:21:46,307
All right, momma, that is enough.

454
00:21:46,308 --> 00:21:49,547
Tell me what
this is about right now.

455
00:21:49,548 --> 00:21:52,268
Look... is this all right?

456
00:21:52,269 --> 00:21:53,668
I mean, this stuff
is just fantastic

457
00:21:53,669 --> 00:22:00,268
for me and I just thought would
you like to see the ring?

458
00:22:00,269 --> 00:22:01,669
The what?

459
00:22:01,909 --> 00:22:02,829
The ring.

460
00:22:03,069 --> 00:22:07,149
It's my secret Mr Quinlan said
I can't keep secrets, but I can.

461
00:22:07,150 --> 00:22:09,229
Except I told Mr Jack in the car.

462
00:22:09,230 --> 00:22:12,309
What are you talking about?

463
00:22:12,310 --> 00:22:14,829
I found it on Black Mountain.

464
00:22:14,830 --> 00:22:16,269
Where the plane crashed.

465
00:22:16,270 --> 00:22:19,590
In the war The B-17.

466
00:22:19,591 --> 00:22:22,191
The B-17?

467
00:22:22,471 --> 00:22:24,670
A B-17 'G' turret

468
00:22:24,671 --> 00:22:28,550
It had the new chin it had double
50 calibre machine-guns.

469
00:22:28,551 --> 00:22:30,230
And that's where I found the ring.

470
00:22:30,231 --> 00:22:30,671
What ring?

471
00:22:30,871 --> 00:22:32,511
Whose ring?

472
00:22:32,512 --> 00:22:34,191
Mr Gordon's.

473
00:22:34,192 --> 00:22:36,711
Well, your dad's.

474
00:22:36,712 --> 00:22:40,111
Before he was, you know killed.

475
00:22:40,112 --> 00:22:41,551
In Belfast?

476
00:22:41,552 --> 00:22:42,592
Yes.

477
00:22:42,832 --> 00:22:44,991
Are you just gonna
let this happen?

478
00:22:44,992 --> 00:22:47,432
My daddy wasn't killed in Belfast.

479
00:22:47,433 --> 00:22:50,672
He died here
a couple of months ago.

480
00:22:50,673 --> 00:22:52,592
And his name wasn't Gordon,
it was Harris.

481
00:22:52,593 --> 00:22:54,312
Chuck Harris.

482
00:22:54,313 --> 00:22:57,392
Wasn't it, mom?

483
00:22:57,393 --> 00:23:02,714
Of course, he couldn't be
your dad You're too young.

484
00:23:02,834 --> 00:23:03,793
Shall I put these away?

485
00:23:03,794 --> 00:23:06,193
Maybe you don't
have a place for them.

486
00:23:06,194 --> 00:23:09,273
I have a place.

487
00:23:09,274 --> 00:23:11,153
Peter,
there's some tools out back.

488
00:23:11,154 --> 00:23:13,554
A crowbar, some hammers.

489
00:23:13,555 --> 00:23:15,514
Would you bring them to me,
please?

490
00:23:15,515 --> 00:23:17,434
What... now?

491
00:23:17,435 --> 00:23:19,874
Yes,
I need to take down this wall.

492
00:23:19,875 --> 00:23:20,634
Stop, momma!

493
00:23:20,635 --> 00:23:21,075
Don't

494
00:23:21,275 --> 00:23:22,034
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

495
00:23:22,035 --> 00:23:22,834
Take it easy!

496
00:23:22,835 --> 00:23:24,194
This was daddy's house!

497
00:23:24,195 --> 00:23:26,035
You are not going to smash it up.

498
00:23:26,036 --> 00:23:27,755
This was
never your daddy's house.

499
00:23:27,756 --> 00:23:29,675
He just let you believe it.

500
00:23:29,676 --> 00:23:31,155
Then whose house is this?

501
00:23:31,156 --> 00:23:34,195
Which of you gentlemen is
going to bring me the tools?

502
00:23:34,196 --> 00:23:38,036
That's what you really want?

503
00:23:39,357 --> 00:23:43,477
He kept all your letters.

504
00:23:43,477 --> 00:23:46,516
I guess you don't
have a place for these.

505
00:23:46,517 --> 00:23:49,396
Oh, I have a place.

506
00:23:49,397 --> 00:23:53,117
Did he have any photographs,
postcards?

507
00:23:53,118 --> 00:23:53,678
Pocket.

508
00:23:53,918 --> 00:23:57,278
Right side.

509
00:24:02,518 --> 00:24:04,637
He never even got to write these.

510
00:24:04,638 --> 00:24:08,478
Ethel Ann maybe we ought
to take some of this stuff down?

511
00:24:08,479 --> 00:24:09,559
No.

512
00:24:10,159 --> 00:24:12,118
Nobody should touch this wall.

513
00:24:12,119 --> 00:24:13,678
We could make an album,

514
00:24:13,679 --> 00:24:16,238
take the photos and
put them in a scrapbook.

515
00:24:16,239 --> 00:24:17,358
This is his wall.

516
00:24:17,359 --> 00:24:18,238
This is his house.

517
00:24:18,239 --> 00:24:19,038
I don't want anybody

518
00:24:19,039 --> 00:24:21,679
Ethel Ann, this is your house.

519
00:24:21,680 --> 00:24:23,239
He left it to you.

520
00:24:23,240 --> 00:24:27,799
He wouldn't like it
you living here every day,

521
00:24:27,800 --> 00:24:31,520
this stuff staring down at you.

522
00:24:32,840 --> 00:24:35,600
He was gonna build a shed out back.

523
00:24:35,601 --> 00:24:38,200
We'll just use the wood.

524
00:24:38,201 --> 00:24:40,920
Do you want us to build you a shed?

525
00:24:40,921 --> 00:24:42,281
No.

526
00:24:43,801 --> 00:24:46,361
No, I want you to board it up.

527
00:24:46,362 --> 00:24:51,321
Don't touch it, just cover it up.

528
00:24:51,322 --> 00:24:55,162
Is that really what you want?

529
00:25:52,126 --> 00:25:58,207
This Teddy who was he?

530
00:26:01,007 --> 00:26:02,687
Jimmy?

531
00:26:05,287 --> 00:26:08,287
Sergeant Teddy Gordon.

532
00:26:08,288 --> 00:26:14,887
Rear gunner on B-17337833.

533
00:26:14,888 --> 00:26:19,327
He crashed June 1st, 1944.

534
00:26:19,328 --> 00:26:23,209
He was killed.

535
00:26:23,489 --> 00:26:25,089
Gordon?

536
00:26:27,289 --> 00:26:31,089
Mrs Gordon.

537
00:26:32,609 --> 00:26:37,249
All those years daddy lived in
another man's house.

538
00:26:37,250 --> 00:26:39,009
I'm getting out of here right now.

539
00:26:39,010 --> 00:26:39,809
Marie, your mother needs you.

540
00:26:39,810 --> 00:26:41,049
You shut your mouth!

541
00:26:41,050 --> 00:26:45,130
Shut your mouth!

542
00:26:46,210 --> 00:26:50,330
He loved you!

543
00:26:50,331 --> 00:26:56,330
In spite of all of this,
he loved you.

544
00:26:56,331 --> 00:27:00,371
But you never did, did you?

545
00:27:00,372 --> 00:27:02,971
And all of his life he knew...

546
00:27:02,972 --> 00:27:08,851
...you locked your love behind
a god-damn wall!

547
00:27:08,852 --> 00:27:11,171
There was no proof.

548
00:27:11,172 --> 00:27:15,492
And it was all I had left of him.

549
00:27:15,493 --> 00:27:19,932
I don't care about him.

550
00:27:19,933 --> 00:27:20,613
You bitch!

551
00:27:20,853 --> 00:27:23,692
